The grounds for divorce vary considerably from country to country. Marriage may be regarded as a social contract or legal status or a combination thereof. Wha marriage is regarded as a contract, the refusal or inability of one of the spouses to perform the obligations stipulated in the contract may constitute a reason for the other party to request a divorce. In contrast, in some countries (e.g. Sweden, Finland, Australia and New Zealand) there is a so-called (absolute divorce), which means that it does not matter why individuals/spouses wish to secede, since couples can secede of their own free will without the need for one party to prove the other party ' s fault or default. Many judicial authorities in several countries have offered both the option of divorce without error as well as divorce for error, for example in many American states or in the Czech Republic. Although divorce laws differ among judicial authorities in States, there are two basic methods of divorce: divorce without error or divorce with error. However, in some judicial authorities, which do not require a party to make a false claim by its partner, the court may still take into account the behaviour of spouses in the division of property and debts and in the evaluation of matters relating to custody, joint care and support for children. In some States, the judicial authorities may force one of the spouses to pay for the counsel of the other party. The laws also differ with regard to the period of time after which divorce becomes effective, as well as the requirements for residence or residence, yet cases of division of property are usually determined by the law of the judicial authorities in which the property is located. In Europe divorce laws vary from country to country, reflecting different legal and cultural traditions.

The measurement of long-term interference (Viry-long-baseline interferometry) is a type of astronomical interferometry used in radio astronomy. In LBI, a signal is collected from an astronomical radio source, such as cosarse stars, using multiple radio telescopes on Earth or in space. The distance betweradio telescopes is thcalculated using the time difference betwethe radio signal and the different telescopes. This allows for the simultaneous detection of an offence by several radio telescopes, which simulates the use of one large telescope of a size equal to the maximum distance betwetelescopes. The data received in the matrix antennas include signal arrival times using a local atomic clock, such as hydrogmess. Later, data are collected with other antenna data that recorded the same radio signal, to produce the final image. The accuracy that can be achieved using an overlap measure is proportional to the frequency of monitoring. The LBI technique allows the distance betwetelescopes to be much greater than that possible using conventional interferometry, which requires the delivery of antennas by a pivot cable, wave guide, optical fibres or any other type of electrical transmission line. More distance can be achieved in LBI by means of the closure technology developed by Roger Jenson in the 1950s, which allows LBI to produce much more accurate images. LBI techniques are used to capture remote cosmic radio sources, and to track spacecraft, as well as other applications in astronomical measurement. The term decolonization was used to refer to cultural decolonization from colonial ideas that made the colony feel inferior. Decolonization issues continue to exist and to be raised contemporaryally. Such issues are increasingly being discussed in Latin America and South Africa under the term "dicolonism" (cultural separation from colonialism). There was momentum for decolonization at the end of the First World War, particularly through the League of Nations, especially for European territories under the control of the Ottoman and Austrian Hungarian empires. Under Article 22 of the Charter of the League of Nations, several States were placed under mandate. The stated intention was to prepare these countries for self-government, but the mandate is oftinterpreted as merely a redistribution of control over the former non-European colonies of defeated powers, especially the German Empire and the Ottoman Empire. This reassignment work continued through the United Nations, with a similar regime of territories under international trusteeship established to modify control over both former colonies and mandated territories. The 1960 United Nations Declaration on the Granting of Independence to Colonial Countries and Peoples was a milestone in decolonization. Researchers have proposed different interpretations of decolonization trends. Two prominent interpretations emphasize the state of the world economy (e.g. whether there is dominance, economic growth or stagnation) and the theory of the world political system (which emphasizes the spread of the model of a nation-state from Western Europe to dependency and contagion, where decolonization takes place in one case leading to subsequent decolonization in other cases). Other interpretations confirmed how the decline in the profitability of colonialism and the costs associated with the empire had led to decolonization. Some explanations confirm how the colonial powers have fought militarily against the rebels in the colonies because of the shift from the conditions of the nineteenth century of strong political will, a tolerant international environment, access to local collaborators, and flexibility in choosing their battles against the circumstances of the twentieth century such as the heroic masses, the hostile superpowers, the lack of collaborators, and restrictive choices.

Public health services are universal and available to all citizens of the State free of charge. In any case, taxes finance the construction and maintenance of health centres and hospitals, with the State spending about 9% of its GDP on the health sector. Statistics for 2012 indicate that there are 1.85 doctors and 2.3 beds in Brazilian hospitals per 1,000 inhabitants. Public health problems persist in Brazil despite the progress made since the establishment of the comprehensive health-care system in 1988, with the main problems to be solved in 2006 being high infant mortality rates (2.51 per cent) and maternal mortality rates (73.1 per 1,000 births). The Brazilian health sector is affected by other figures, such as the number of deaths from non-communicable diseases, such as cardiovascular diseases (151.7 deaths per 100,000 inhabitants) and cancer (72.7 deaths per 100,000 inhabitants). Preventable external factors such as car accidents, violence and suicide caused 14.9% of the country ' s total deaths. The Brazilian health system was ranked 125th out of 191 countries valued by the World Health Organization (WHO) in 2000. The Federal Constitution and the National Education Controls Act and its foundations provide for the duty of the Federative Government of Brazil, its states, federal provinces and municipalities to administer and regulate their own education systems. The Constitution allocates 25% of the State budget and 18% of federal and local taxes to the education sector. The literacy rate was 93.4% of Brazilians, according to figures from the Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics (IBGE) in 2019, meaning that 11.3% of the population (6.6%) are still illiterate, with the literacy rate reaching about 97% in some states such as Rio de Janeiro and Santa Catarina, with functional illiteracy equivalent to 21.6% of the population.

Earth Day, an annual event celebrated around the world on April 22 to show support for environmental protection. Earth Day was first celebrated in 1970, and now includes events organized worldwide by the Earth Day Network in more than 193 countries around the world. The historic Paris Convention was signed by the United States, China and some 120 other countries on Earth Day in 2016. The signing of the Convention included a key requirement for the entry into force of the historic draft of the Climate Protection Treaty, adopted unanimously by 195 States present at the 2015 United Nations Climate Change Conference in Paris. Peace activist John McConnell, at the 1969 UNESCO Conference in San Francisco, proposed a day to honour the Earth and the concept of peace, which was first celebrated on March 21, 1970, the first spring day in the northern hemisphere. The Nature Balance Day was later endorsed in a declaration writtby McConnell and signed by Secretary-General U Thant at the United Nations. A month later, American Senator Gaylord Nelson founded a separate Earth Day as the first environmental awareness day on April 22, 1970, and Nelson later received the Presidential Order of Freedom in recognition of his work. WhLand Day was set on April 22, in the United States, an organization launched by Dennis Hayes, the main national coordinator in 1970, made Earth Day a world day in 1990, and evorganized the event in 141 countries. Many societies are celebrating Earth Week, an entire week of activities focusing on the environmental issues facing the world. The Science March took place on Earth Day in 2017 (22 April 2017) and was followed by the People ' s Climate Alert (29 April 2017).

Thermocouple is an electrical component used to measure temperatures. This type of measurement is of great importance in measuring high-value temperatures. One of its advantages is low manufacturing cost, strong design and user-friendly especially whused in complex and variable standard systems. The double consists of two different metal that are connected to each other at the tip of the double. Whthere is a thermal variation at the tip of the double which in turn contains the sides of the different metals, there is an electrical tension proportional to the temperature passing through each of the metals. The more heat the metal, the more power it generates. So each side passes to a metal, different heat from the other metal corridor, and two different electric currents reach the other end. At this end, which binds the metal together, an electrical effort is generated because there is a variation in currents. An electronic component measures this generated effort, converts its value as needed to the thermal value shown on display, or passes the value to another component for use in another standard machine or the like. The scientific background of the modus operandi depends on the Sibek coefficient discovered by the German scientist Thomas Sebeck. Whthe heat of a metal changes, its electrons move faster. Whthe velocity of electrons in the two related metals varies in the thermocouple, the electrons overlap with each other where the metal meets. And that's where there's a surplus of electrons on one side, and a shortage of electrons on the other. This difference generates an electrical current that relates to the metal type on the one hand, and heat on the other. This current is called the electro-thermal current. Jerusalem is characterized by the Mediterranean climate (Csa Cobin classification), with a dry hot summer, and a mildly cold winter. Snow usually falls once or twice during winter, although the city experiences a high snowfall once every three to four years, on average, with a short-lived accumulation. January is the coldest month of the year, with an average temperature of 9.1°C (48.4°C); July and August are the hottest, with an average temperature of 24.2°C (75.6°C), and summer months are usually dry. The average annual rainfall is about 537 mm (21 inches) betweOctober and May, while the other months are mostly out of rainfall. Snowfall is not common, but heavy snowfall is rare. Jerusalem received more than 30 cm (12 inches) of snow on December 13, 2013, which almost crippled the city. With average summer temperatures similar to the coasts, the Mediterranean sea influence is strong, especially givthat Jerusalem is on a latitude similar to the warm deserts not far to the east. The highest temperature recorded in Jerusalem was 44.4 °C (111.9°C) on 28 and 30 August 1881, and the lowest temperature recorded on 25 January 1907 was -6.7 °C (19.9°C). Most air pollution in Jerusalem comes from car traffic. Many major streets in Jerusalem have not bebuilt to accommodate this large volume of traffic, resulting in traffic congestion and more carbon monoxide emissions in the air.

Low-mass stars consume their fuel very slowly and react at lower temperatures (about 12 million degrees Celsius). The Litseng diamond mine is located in the Kingdom of Lesotho, a South African State that is closed and not at sea, owned by Jim Diamond and the Government of Lesotho. It is the largest diamond mine in the world, where it descends below ground to a depth of ~3,100 metres (10,000 feet). It has a very low ore (less than 2 carats/100 tons) but is well known for producing large pieces of diamonds, with the highest proportion of large diamonds (above 10 carats), giving it a dollar value per carat higher than any other diamond mine. The global average is about $81 per carat, while the average for the first six months of 2007 was over $1894 per carat. Because of the extreme depth of the mine, the mine ' s temperature drops to sub-20 degrees Celsius, and snow falls in winter routinely, but it is unusual for hot Africa.
